# Testing — {{.ProjectName}}

## Framework

- Use the standard library `testing` package
- Use `httptest.NewServer` and `httptest.NewRecorder` for handler tests
- `testify/assert` and `testify/require` are allowed for cleaner assertions but not required

## Table-Driven Tests

Prefer table-driven tests for functions with multiple input/output cases:

```go
func TestParseAge(t *testing.T) {
    tests := []struct {
        name    string
        input   string
        want    int
        wantErr bool
    }{
        {name: "valid age", input: "25", want: 25},
        {name: "negative age", input: "-1", wantErr: true},
        {name: "non-numeric", input: "abc", wantErr: true},
    }

    for _, tt := range tests {
        t.Run(tt.name, func(t *testing.T) {
            got, err := ParseAge(tt.input)
            if tt.wantErr {
                require.Error(t, err)
                return
            }
            require.NoError(t, err)
            assert.Equal(t, tt.want, got)
        })
    }
}
```

## Handler Tests

- Use `httptest.NewRecorder` for unit-testing individual handlers
- Inject mock services into the handler struct — test the HTTP layer in isolation
- Assert on status code, response body, and content-type header

## Mocking

- Mock at interface boundaries: define a mock struct that implements the service interface
- Keep mocks in the test file or a `_test.go` file in the same package
- For complex mocks, use `github.com/stretchr/testify/mock` or hand-rolled structs with call tracking

## Conventions

- Name tests descriptively: `TestGetUser_ReturnsNotFound_WhenUserDoesNotExist`
- Use `t.Helper()` in test utility functions so failures report the caller's line
- Run tests with `-race` in CI to catch data races
- Use `t.Parallel()` for independent tests to speed up the suite
- Test files are `*_test.go` in the same package as the code they test
